Shuvalov was born on 15 November 1923. In 1941 he entered the army directly from school. Shuvalov participated in the battles of Moscow, Stalingrad and Kursk. He served until the end of the war in 1945 and was awarded the Order of the Red Star. In 1946 Shuvalov entered Moscow State University to study physics, graduating in 1951. He then worked for the Hydroproject Institute for five years. In 1956 Shuvalov joined the Institute of Crystallography studying under Alexei Vasilievich Shubnikov; he gained his doctorate in 1971. He was then appointed a professor at the Institute of Crystallography. In 1972 Shuvalov created the Laboratory of Phase Transitions of which he was the head for over 20 years.

Shuvalov's work was in the fields of mathematics and crystallography, specifically the use of group theory to analyse the phase changes occurring in ferroelectric and ferroelastic crystals. He published more than 700 papers during his scientific career and held over 20 patents. Between 1956 and 1974, Shuvalov was a leader in the field of symmetry considerations in the crystallography and crystal physics of ferroelectrics... He established a classification of ferroelectrics based on their crystal symmetry... He also discovered a new class of crystals with superionic conductivity (superprotonic conductors).

Shuvalov was editor of Kristallografija from 1997 to 2004. He also served on the editorial boards of international journals such as Condensed Matter News, Crystallography Reviews, Ferroelectrics, Ferroelectrics Letters, and Zeitschrift für Kristallographie.

Summary: 
Lev Aleksandrovich Shuvalov (November 15, 1923 – December 6, 2004) was a prominent Soviet mathematician and crystallographer known for his pioneering work on symmetry in ferroelectric and ferroelastic crystal phase changes, as well as the discovery of crystals with superionic conductivity. He served in the Soviet Army during WWII (fighting in Moscow, Stalingrad, and Kursk) and earned the Order of the Red Star. After graduating from Moscow State University with a physics degree, he eventually joined the Shubnikov Institute of Crystallography, where he earned his doctorate under Alexei Vasilievich Shubnikov and headed the Laboratory of Phase Transitions for over 20 years. He was awarded the USSR State Prize (1975) and the Federov Prize (1994). He also edited and served on the boards of several major scientific journals. This comprehensive profile provides all the necessary biographical, educational, and professional data to cross-reference against your specific clues.
