Evidence in page: 
Nina Evgenievna Vedeneyeva (Russian: Нина Евгеньевна Веденеева; 1 December 1882 – 31 December 1955) was a Soviet physicist involved in the study of mineral crystals and their coloration. Heading numerous departments at such institutions as the All-USSR Institute of Mineral Resources, the Institute of Geological Sciences and the Institute of Crystallography, she conducted research into color variants of clay minerals and classifying clays which occurred in organic dyes. She was noted for development and design of instruments to improve the methods of optical crystallography. She was the last partner-muse of the poet Sophia Parnok and was awarded the Stalin Prize and Order of Lenin for her scientific studies and inventions.

Nina Evgenievna Vedeneyeva was born on 1 December 1882 in Tbilisi, capital of the Caucasus Viceroyalty, Russian Empire... on 28 July 1903 at the Russian Orthodox Church in Brussels, she and Sirotinsky married. He finished his studies and the couple returned to his parental home in Nikolaev, where their son, Yevgeny was born at the end of the year.

In 1930, Vedeneyeva became the department head of crystal optics at the All-USSR Institute of Mineral Resources in Moscow... In 1932, she moved out of the apartment she had shared since 1918 with Avramenko, moved in with her son, and around the same time her relationship with Parnok intensified. Between January 1932 and August 1933, Parnok wrote thirty poems in two cycles to Vedeneyeva... In 1952, Vedeneyeva was awarded the Stalin Prize in the third degree for inventions and improvements in methods of production in the field of exploration and mining and in 1954, she was presented with the Order of Lenin.

Summary: 
Nina Vedeneyeva (December 1, 1882 – December 31, 1955) was a prominent Soviet physicist renowned for her work in optical crystallography and the study of mineral crystals and clay coloration. She held department head positions at various prestigious Soviet institutions and won the Stalin Prize (1952) and the Order of Lenin (1954). Personally, she was married to Leonid Ivanovich Sirotinsky, with whom she had a son, and later became famously known as the last partner and muse of the poet Sophia Parnok. This comprehensive overview provides key dates, career milestones, and personal details to help cross-reference against any specific clues.
