Pyotr Kozmich Frolov (Russian: Пётр Козьми́ч Фроло́в; 27 January [O.S. 16 January] 1775[1] – 22 December [O.S. 10 December] 1839[2]) was a Russian mining engineer and inventor who built the first horse-railway in the Russian Empire in 1809. He elaborated on various canal projects and other artificial water constructions. Frolov also contributed to the development of scientific research and to the culture of the Altay region. His activities as a head of the Kolyvano-Voskresensk factories promoted a great advance of Russian technology in the beginning of the 20th century.[citation needed] He was appointed a senator in 1831.

Summary: 
Pyotr Kozmich Frolov (born January 27, 1775 – died December 22, 1839) was a prominent Russian mining engineer and inventor. His most notable achievements include building the first horse-drawn railway in the Russian Empire in 1809, working on various canal and artificial water construction projects, and serving as the head of the Kolyvano-Voskresensk factories. Additionally, he was appointed a senator in 1831. This comprehensive biographical information provides the essential details needed to evaluate if he matches any specific clues.
