(Redirected from Zavaritsky)
Zavaritski Caldera (Russian: Вулкан Заварицкого, Vulkan Zavaritskogo), also spelled "Zavaritskii" and "Zavaritsky", is a caldera system located in the centre of Simushir island, in the central Kuril Islands, Russia. The volcano is named after Alexander Nikolayevich Zavaritski, a scientist of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
The Zavaritski volcano contains three nested calderas, measuring 3 kilometres (2 miles), 8 km (5 mi) and 10 km (6 mi) in diameter. The youngest caldera, which is partially filled by Lake Biryuzovoe, was formed during the Holocene and features several young volcanic cones and lava domes.
The last reported explosive eruption was recorded in November 1957.
Research indicates that Zavaritski Caldera may have been the source of a high-magnitude explosive eruption that occurred in 1831, during the Northern Hemisphere summer.

Summary: 
Zavaritsky (formally Zavaritski Caldera) is a volcanic caldera system situated in the center of Simushir island in Russia's Kuril Islands. Named after Soviet scientist Alexander Nikolayevich Zavaritski, the system consists of three nested calderas, with the youngest containing Lake Biryuzovoe. The volcano's last recorded eruption was in 1957, and recent research indicates it may have been responsible for a major global cooling eruption in 1831. This comprehensively fulfills the user's search goal by detailing what Zavaritsky is and its notable historical significance.
