Yakov Grigorevich Sinai was born into a Russian Jewish academic family on September 21, 1935, in Moscow, Soviet Union (now Russia). His parents, Nadezda Kagan and Gregory Sinai, were both microbiologists. His grandfather, Veniamin Kagan, headed the Department of Differential Geometry at Moscow State University and was a major influence on Sinai's life.

Sinai received his bachelor's and master's degrees from Moscow State University. In 1960, he earned his Ph.D., also from Moscow State; his adviser was Andrey Kolmogorov. Together with Kolmogorov, he showed that even for "unpredictable" dynamic systems, the level of unpredictability of motion can be described mathematically... 

In 1963, Sinai introduced the idea of dynamical billiards, also known as "Sinai Billiards"... Also in 1963, Sinai announced a proof of the ergodic hypothesis for a gas consisting of n hard spheres confined to a box... 

From 1960 to 1971, Sinai was a researcher in the Laboratory of Probabilistic and Statistical Methods at Moscow State University. In 1971 he accepted a position as senior researcher at the Landau Institute for Theoretical Physics in Russia, while continuing to teach at Moscow State... 

Since 1993, Sinai has been a professor of mathematics at Princeton University, while maintaining his position at the Landau Institute. For the 1997–98 academic year, he was the Thomas Jones Professor at Princeton, and in 2005, the Moore Distinguished Scholar at the California Institute of Technology.

In 2002, Sinai won the Nemmers Prize for his "revolutionizing" work on dynamical systems, statistical mechanics, probability theory, and statistical physics... In 2013, Sinai received the Leroy P. Steele Prize for Lifetime Achievement. In 2014, the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters awarded him the Abel Prize, for his contributions to dynamical systems, ergodic theory, and mathematical physics... 

Other awards won by Sinai include the Boltzmann Medal (1986), the Dannie Heineman Prize for Mathematical Physics (1990), the Dirac Prize (1992), the Wolf Prize in Mathematics (1997), the Lagrange Prize (2008) and the Henri Poincaré Prize (2009)... 

Sinai has authored more than 250 papers and books... Sinai is married to mathematician and physicist Elena B. Vul. The couple have written several joint papers.

Summary: 
Yakov Grigorevich Sinai, born in 1935 in Moscow to an academic family, is a renowned Russian-American mathematician. He earned his degrees, including a Ph.D. under Andrey Kolmogorov, from Moscow State University. His academic career spans positions at Moscow State University, the Landau Institute for Theoretical Physics, and Princeton University, where he has been a professor since 1993. Sinai has made groundbreaking contributions to dynamical systems, mathematical physics, and probability theory, including the development of Kolmogorov–Sinai entropy and Sinai Billiards. He has authored over 250 papers and books and has been recognized with numerous prestigious awards, including the Nemmers Prize (2002), the Wolf Prize (1997), the Leroy P. Steele Prize (2013), and the Abel Prize (2014). He is married to Elena B. Vul, with whom he has co-authored several papers.
