Albert Nikolayevich Shiryaev (born October 12, 1934) is a prominent Soviet and Russian mathematician renowned for his extensive work in probability theory, statistics, and financial mathematics. He graduated from Moscow State University in 1957 and completed his candidate degree under the renowned Andrey Kolmogorov in 1961. Shiryaev has built a distinguished academic career with long-term affiliations at the Steklov Mathematical Institute, Moscow State University, and the University of Manchester. Over his career, he has supervised over 50 doctoral dissertations, published widely, and held leadership roles including president of the Bernoulli Society and the Bachelier Finance Society. He is a full member of the Russian Academy of Sciences and has been honored with numerous prestigious awards such as the Markov Prize, Kolmogorov Prize, Humboldt Prize, and Chebyshev gold medal. This information fully satisfies the user's goal of checking Albert Shiryaev's biography.
