He was born in 1879 in Brest-Litovsk (then Russia, currently Brest, Belarus). At a young age, he became interested in mathematics, and became a doctoral student under David Hilbert in Gottingen. After completing his doctoral thesis in 1914, for more than 10 years he served as an assistant of Albert Einstein, working with him in his (unsuccessful) attempts to build a unified field theory. Later Einstein facilitated Grommer’s contacts with Russian physicists to arrange his appointment as a professor of the Belarusian State University in Minsk in 1929. Shortly afterwards, Grommer was elected as a member of the Belarusian Academy of Sciences. Grommer made contributions to mathematical physics, complex analysis, and analytic number theory.

Summary: 
Jacob Grommer was born in 1879 in the city of Brest-Litovsk. He was educated in Gottingen, where he was a doctoral student under David Hilbert, completing his thesis in 1914. For his career, Grommer worked as an assistant to Albert Einstein for over ten years, collaborating on the unified field theory. In 1929, he was appointed as a professor at the Belarusian State University in Minsk and subsequently elected to the Belarusian Academy of Sciences. His work included notable contributions to mathematical physics, complex analysis, and analytic number theory. This information successfully answers all aspects of the user's query.
